1
00:00:25,626 --> 00:00:27,595
[ School Bell Rings ]

2
00:00:35,569 --> 00:00:39,340
Ambition? Well,
I want to do something that's
going to be lastingly useful...

3
00:00:39,373 --> 00:00:43,411
and leave some sort
of mark behind me,
not just a blank space.

4
00:00:43,444 --> 00:00:47,615
I think my ambition in life
is to be famous,
but I'm not quite sure.

5
00:01:05,299 --> 00:01:07,468
[ Young Man ]
I've never experienced
another generation,

6
00:01:07,501 --> 00:01:10,171
but I do feel we'll
have something to say.

7
00:01:10,204 --> 00:01:13,241
We'll make a gigantic splash
in the world to come.

8
00:01:13,274 --> 00:01:15,409
There's always
a change going on.

9
00:01:15,443 --> 00:01:17,345
You never know
what's gonna happen next.

10
00:01:17,378 --> 00:01:19,647
You never know what
new clothes you're gonna have.

11
00:01:19,680 --> 00:01:21,849
You never know
what the new records
are gonna be.

12
00:01:21,882 --> 00:01:24,252
My stack of records
keeps getting larger.

13
00:01:39,267 --> 00:01:42,136
You know how parents are.
They always bug you--
where you're going,

14
00:01:42,170 --> 00:01:43,804
when you're getting home,
who you went with,

15
00:01:43,837 --> 00:01:46,674
what time you're gonna be back,
don't stay on the phone
too long.

16
00:01:46,707 --> 00:01:49,343
Then you get your own car,
and you're free a little bit.

17
00:01:49,377 --> 00:01:51,412
But they're still
holding on the rope.

18
00:02:09,730 --> 00:02:14,702
[ Speaking German ]

19
00:02:27,415 --> 00:02:30,384
[ American Girl Narrating ]
We're teenagers.

20
00:02:31,452 --> 00:02:33,687
But we didn't always exist.

21
00:02:35,489 --> 00:02:37,658
We were a wartime invention.

22
00:02:41,262 --> 00:02:43,297
Who would we become?

23
00:02:44,332 --> 00:02:46,734
Who would decide it?

24
00:02:46,767 --> 00:02:48,402
The adults?

25
00:02:51,439 --> 00:02:52,773
Or us?

26
00:03:02,350 --> 00:03:04,752
[ Hoofbeats Clopping ]

27
00:03:06,620 --> 00:03:08,556
[ Bell Tolling ]

28
00:03:15,863 --> 00:03:17,765
[ Cheering ]

29
00:03:30,511 --> 00:03:33,347
[ British Boy Narrating ]
First we were just children.

30
00:03:34,815 --> 00:03:36,717
That's how they thought of us.

31
00:03:38,786 --> 00:03:42,623
And then all of a sudden
we were supposed to be adults.

32
00:03:47,595 --> 00:03:51,365
Twelve years old,
and I'd be off to work
in the factory.

33
00:03:54,502 --> 00:03:56,504
I worked 74 hours a week.

34
00:03:58,038 --> 00:04:01,342
6:00 in the morning
till 5:30 at night.

35
00:04:01,375 --> 00:04:03,411
Saturdays till noon.

36
00:04:05,479 --> 00:04:07,681
My hands were bruised and cut.

37
00:04:10,050 --> 00:04:12,353
I felt like a slave.

38
00:04:20,528 --> 00:04:23,431
[ Man On Recording ]
Children have always worked,

39
00:04:23,464 --> 00:04:26,534
but it is only since
the reign of the machine...

40
00:04:26,567 --> 00:04:30,538
that their work has been
synonymous with slavery.

41
00:04:32,406 --> 00:04:35,609
There is no more
terrible page in history...

42
00:04:35,643 --> 00:04:39,079
than that which records
the enslavement
of mere babies...

43
00:04:39,112 --> 00:04:41,849
by the industrial revolution.

44
00:04:44,985 --> 00:04:47,688
[ American Girl Narrating ]
Adults knew it wasn't right.

45
00:04:50,358 --> 00:04:52,660
They wanted to protect us.

46
00:04:54,662 --> 00:04:57,898
So governments started
to make child labor
against the law.

47
00:05:03,837 --> 00:05:05,739
I started going to school.

48
00:05:08,108 --> 00:05:10,878
I loved having fun
with my friends.

49
00:05:12,846 --> 00:05:14,615
We were young,

50
00:05:15,449 --> 00:05:17,685
and we were allowed to be.

51
00:05:19,787 --> 00:05:22,723
There was a second stage
of life now.

52
00:05:25,726 --> 00:05:27,795
"Adolescence."

53
00:05:36,904 --> 00:05:39,740
[ British Boy ]
In the factory
we were prisoners,

54
00:05:40,608 --> 00:05:42,976
but in the streets...

55
00:05:43,010 --> 00:05:44,812
we were free.

56
00:05:49,417 --> 00:05:51,619
The cities
were fast and hard.

57
00:05:52,953 --> 00:05:54,588
So were we.

58
00:05:57,157 --> 00:05:59,927
We formed gangs
that roamed the streets.

59
00:06:01,695 --> 00:06:04,364
"Hooligans"
is what the police called us.

60
00:06:05,165 --> 00:06:07,568
We carried knives.

61
00:06:07,601 --> 00:06:10,504
We robbed...
and killed.

62
00:06:12,640 --> 00:06:15,142
Youth were a problem...

63
00:06:15,175 --> 00:06:17,445
that had to be controlled.

64
00:06:18,579 --> 00:06:21,148
[ Man On Recording ]
My brother Scouts,

65
00:06:21,181 --> 00:06:25,953
you are doing much
to prevent the present
disgraceful waste...

66
00:06:25,986 --> 00:06:27,755
of human materials...

67
00:06:27,788 --> 00:06:30,090
and showing
your poorer brothers...

68
00:06:30,123 --> 00:06:32,893
how to be good,
successful men.

69
00:06:32,926 --> 00:06:35,128
[ Cheering ]

70
00:06:35,162 --> 00:06:37,998
[ British Boy ]
One man thought
he'd found a solution...

71
00:06:38,031 --> 00:06:40,534
to the problem of youth.

72
00:06:41,802 --> 00:06:43,904
A soldier called
Robert Baden-Powell...

73
00:06:43,937 --> 00:06:46,874
wrote a military
training manual for the young.

74
00:06:47,808 --> 00:06:50,444
Scouting for Boys
it was called.

75
00:06:51,211 --> 00:06:53,681
It was a manifesto
for a movement--

76
00:06:54,548 --> 00:06:56,650
the Boy Scouts.

77
00:06:56,684 --> 00:06:58,819
[ Baden-Powell ]
You are tested
on your honor...

78
00:06:58,852 --> 00:07:03,090
to do your best to carry out
the Scout Promise,

79
00:07:03,123 --> 00:07:06,527
which is to work
for God and the king.

80
00:07:07,961 --> 00:07:11,565
Tracking and camping
had always been
a fantasy for me.

81
00:07:12,666 --> 00:07:15,235
I'd yearned
for an awfully big adventure,

82
00:07:15,268 --> 00:07:17,437
and here it was.

83
00:07:19,707 --> 00:07:22,676
[ American Girl ]
The Scouts came to America too.

84
00:07:22,710 --> 00:07:26,680
Hundreds of thousands
of boys joined.

85
00:07:26,714 --> 00:07:28,516
They learned patriotism,

86
00:07:28,549 --> 00:07:31,985
courage and self-reliance.

87
00:07:32,019 --> 00:07:36,690
[ Baden-Powell ]
Once a Scout, always a Scout.

88
00:07:36,724 --> 00:07:40,227
[ British Boy ]
I believed
what Baden-Powell said--

89
00:07:40,260 --> 00:07:42,530
"The Scout
is loyal to the king,

90
00:07:42,563 --> 00:07:46,534
to his officers,
his parents and country.

91
00:07:46,567 --> 00:07:48,936
He must stick to them
through thick and thin."

92
00:07:51,271 --> 00:07:53,240
We went from
rat-faced slum kids...

93
00:07:53,273 --> 00:07:56,043
to fit and healthy soldiers,

94
00:07:57,177 --> 00:07:59,046
primed for war.

95
00:08:02,015 --> 00:08:04,618
[ Crowd Cheering ]

96
00:08:06,920 --> 00:08:12,993
[ Man On Recording ]
Today, England is off to war.

97
00:08:13,026 --> 00:08:17,931
Meet the fall
with the cry of liberty.

98
00:08:19,767 --> 00:08:21,869
If you didn't join up,

99
00:08:21,902 --> 00:08:24,037
you were letting
everybody down.

100
00:08:25,673 --> 00:08:27,641
They made sure you knew it.

101
00:08:40,253 --> 00:08:42,289
[ Crowd Cheering ]

102
00:08:42,322 --> 00:08:47,094
[ German Girl ]
In Germany, the news of war
was intoxicating.

103
00:08:47,127 --> 00:08:49,262
** [ Singing ]

104
00:08:49,296 --> 00:08:52,566
There were bands playing,
flags flying.

105
00:08:54,602 --> 00:08:57,270
What drove us was
a feeling of adulthood...

106
00:08:57,304 --> 00:08:59,573
burning up inside.

107
00:09:00,674 --> 00:09:04,845
Half the population
was under the age of 22.

108
00:09:04,878 --> 00:09:08,148
Almost all the boys applied
for military service.

109
00:09:09,683 --> 00:09:11,284
13- or 14-year-olds...

110
00:09:11,318 --> 00:09:15,022
were crushed
if they were rejected
by the recruiting officers.

111
00:09:22,930 --> 00:09:25,565
[ British Boy ]
Europe tore itself apart.

112
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:29,770
And then the Americans came.

113
00:09:29,803 --> 00:09:32,039
[ Man On Recording ]
More than two million soldiers,

114
00:09:32,072 --> 00:09:34,975
fully equipped
and indomitable in spirit,

115
00:09:35,008 --> 00:09:39,947
were safely transported
across 3,000 miles of seas,

116
00:09:39,980 --> 00:09:42,249
where they turned
the tide of battle,

117
00:09:42,282 --> 00:09:44,351
one imperishable glory...

118
00:09:44,384 --> 00:09:50,190
and triumph to the greatest war
that the world has ever known.

119
00:09:50,223 --> 00:09:53,861
[ British Boy ]
They brought new music,
dances and films.

120
00:09:54,995 --> 00:09:59,232
American culture
started to spread.

121
00:09:59,266 --> 00:10:02,102
[ Man On Recording ]
Our boys made good in France.

122
00:10:02,135 --> 00:10:05,873
The word "American"
has a new meaning in Europe.

123
00:10:07,274 --> 00:10:09,042
[ Cheering ]

124
00:10:33,767 --> 00:10:35,969
[ German Girl ]
When my brother died
in the war,

125
00:10:37,470 --> 00:10:42,810
they sent us a frame
that said
"Died on the field of honor."

126
00:10:43,977 --> 00:10:46,680
There is no field of honor.

127
00:10:48,015 --> 00:10:50,918
An entire generation
was gutted.

128
00:10:51,885 --> 00:10:55,022
We lost all loyalty and trust.

129
00:10:58,826 --> 00:11:01,161
[ British Boy ]
We were shell-shocked.

130
00:11:02,863 --> 00:11:05,933
The pound of the guns
drove us mad.

131
00:11:07,835 --> 00:11:10,804
Millions of young men
were massacred.

132
00:11:13,774 --> 00:11:16,844
The old had sent us to die,

133
00:11:16,877 --> 00:11:18,946
and we hated them.

134
00:11:54,281 --> 00:11:59,286
[ American Girl ]
After the war,
everyone wanted to be born anew,

135
00:11:59,319 --> 00:12:01,188
to blot out the past.

136
00:12:03,490 --> 00:12:06,159
There was this reckless
sense of release,

137
00:12:08,061 --> 00:12:11,899
and I felt a kind of
wildness inside.

138
00:12:11,932 --> 00:12:13,867
[ Man On Recording ]
What do they want?

139
00:12:13,901 --> 00:12:16,336
They say, "We want beer."

140
00:12:16,369 --> 00:12:20,841
Spending their money,
debauching their character,

141
00:12:20,874 --> 00:12:23,110
rotting their bodies...

142
00:12:23,143 --> 00:12:25,245
and jeopardizing
their immortal souls.

143
00:12:30,017 --> 00:12:33,987
[ American Girl ]
My father says
I can't go out every night.

144
00:12:34,021 --> 00:12:36,857
But what on earth
does he want me to do?

145
00:12:36,890 --> 00:12:39,259
Just sit around
at home all evening?

146
00:12:41,028 --> 00:12:43,864
I don't trust
my parents anymore.

147
00:12:43,897 --> 00:12:45,899
I just want to be
with my friends.

148
00:12:48,368 --> 00:12:51,171
Our world is speedy,

149
00:12:51,204 --> 00:12:53,340
and they're old.

150
00:12:58,545 --> 00:13:01,481
[ Young Woman On Recording ]
The power of today
is in our hands.

151
00:13:01,514 --> 00:13:06,519
We who number ourselves
among the so-called
wild and wicked youth...

152
00:13:06,553 --> 00:13:11,058
would prefer to go out
with drums beating
and bugles blowing.

153
00:13:12,559 --> 00:13:15,095
We want to be young
before we're old.

154
00:13:15,128 --> 00:13:19,532
[ American Girl ]
They call us flappers,
flaming youth.

155
00:13:19,566 --> 00:13:25,405
The times have made us
awfully experienced
for our age.

156
00:13:28,075 --> 00:13:30,610
[ British Boy ]
I got all the new jazz records.

157
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:34,581
My mum thought
it was awful noise.

158
00:13:34,614 --> 00:13:37,050
She asked me why it was good,
and I said,

159
00:13:37,084 --> 00:13:39,286
"Because it comes from America."

160
00:13:42,555 --> 00:13:44,357
[ German Girl ]
You'd hear people say,

161
00:13:44,391 --> 00:13:48,228
"Those who get the youth
get the future."

162
00:13:49,930 --> 00:13:52,599
Our parents
had ruined Germany,

163
00:13:52,632 --> 00:13:55,402
and we wanted
a new kind of community.

164
00:13:58,105 --> 00:14:01,341
So we joined youth groups.

165
00:14:01,374 --> 00:14:04,945
There had been youth movements
even before the war.

166
00:14:04,978 --> 00:14:07,447
Workers' youth groups,
Jewish youth groups,

167
00:14:10,017 --> 00:14:13,887
but the most important group
was the Wandervogel--

168
00:14:13,921 --> 00:14:16,256
"Wandering Birds."

169
00:14:18,491 --> 00:14:22,495
Our teachers and our parents
didn't understand us.

170
00:14:22,529 --> 00:14:25,265
So we created our own world.

171
00:14:26,399 --> 00:14:29,036
Youth were leading youth.

172
00:14:31,038 --> 00:14:33,106
We'd run through forests,

173
00:14:33,140 --> 00:14:36,009
lay together at bonfires,

174
00:14:36,043 --> 00:14:38,278
make flower wreaths
and photos,

175
00:14:38,311 --> 00:14:40,981
sing and dance.

176
00:14:41,014 --> 00:14:43,683
Then drop off our clothes...

177
00:14:43,716 --> 00:14:46,186
and feel free.

178
00:14:48,555 --> 00:14:50,924
[ Chanting ]

179
00:14:52,192 --> 00:14:54,494
[ American Girl ]
To be young was the style.

180
00:14:56,329 --> 00:14:58,531
And it was for sale.

181
00:14:58,565 --> 00:15:00,500
[ German Girl ]
Records,

182
00:15:00,533 --> 00:15:03,403
cigarettes, perfume.

183
00:15:03,436 --> 00:15:07,407
[ British Boy ]
And all those glamorous
Hollywood stars to admire.

184
00:15:07,440 --> 00:15:09,709
I wanted to be like Valentino.

185
00:15:09,742 --> 00:15:11,678
He always got the girls.

186
00:15:11,711 --> 00:15:17,084
[ American Girl ]
When he died, we rushed
the funeral by the thousands.

187
00:15:17,117 --> 00:15:19,419
They called it a riot.

188
00:15:22,089 --> 00:15:24,992
[ British Boy ]
I wish I could have been there.

189
00:15:34,467 --> 00:15:38,071
** [ Jazz ]

190
00:16:00,460 --> 00:16:03,196
[ British Boy ]
In Britain
there was a new breed,

191
00:16:03,230 --> 00:16:06,233
and we defined ourselves
by our youth.

192
00:16:09,302 --> 00:16:12,439
They called us
the Bright Young People.

193
00:16:14,241 --> 00:16:18,078
It started with a few girls
who liked dressing up,

194
00:16:18,111 --> 00:16:20,247
doing hoaxes
and treasure hunts,

195
00:16:20,280 --> 00:16:22,449
making a fool of everyone.

196
00:16:23,316 --> 00:16:25,352
We took it all very seriously.

197
00:16:28,121 --> 00:16:30,257
Except when we didn't.

198
00:16:35,395 --> 00:16:39,166
The police were trying
to shut down
all of London's nightlife.

199
00:16:42,235 --> 00:16:44,404
So we created our own.

200
00:17:15,635 --> 00:17:18,271
[ No Audible Dialogue ]

201
00:17:33,553 --> 00:17:37,056
[ British Boy ]
There was this one girl
who shined especially bright.

202
00:17:40,127 --> 00:17:42,129
Her name was Brenda Dean Paul.

203
00:17:52,439 --> 00:17:55,575
Brenda hit the scene in 1926.

204
00:17:56,643 --> 00:17:58,545
She was 19.

205
00:18:04,751 --> 00:18:07,320
She came from a broken home.

206
00:18:08,621 --> 00:18:10,590
Longed to be famous.

207
00:18:10,623 --> 00:18:12,359
[ No Audible Dialogue ]

208
00:18:14,927 --> 00:18:16,863
She played many parts,
but...

209
00:18:16,896 --> 00:18:22,669
the most convincing
was her role as life and soul
of the party.

210
00:18:26,906 --> 00:18:28,475
Pajama parties,

211
00:18:28,508 --> 00:18:31,244
Greek parties,
Russian parties,

212
00:18:31,278 --> 00:18:33,213
sailor parties,
American parties,

213
00:18:33,246 --> 00:18:36,683
murder parties,
baby parties.

214
00:18:41,221 --> 00:18:44,123
We called them
"freak" parties.

215
00:18:45,392 --> 00:18:48,528
And it didn't take long
for them to become big affairs.

216
00:19:00,673 --> 00:19:04,611
Girls were like boys,
and the boys like girls.

217
00:19:06,279 --> 00:19:08,581
Sometimes you couldn't even
tell us apart.

218
00:19:09,749 --> 00:19:11,651
We liked it that way.

219
00:19:13,953 --> 00:19:17,524
A couple of gossip columnists
wrote it all up in the papers.

220
00:19:18,358 --> 00:19:20,293
They made it into...

221
00:19:21,861 --> 00:19:24,163
a "movement."

222
00:19:35,542 --> 00:19:37,377
But for Brenda--

223
00:19:37,410 --> 00:19:41,214
once she started
she couldn't stop.

224
00:19:42,649 --> 00:19:45,652
She crashed her car,
and then she fell ill.

225
00:19:46,986 --> 00:19:49,322
Perhaps it was
all the late nights.

226
00:19:50,022 --> 00:19:52,225
Or perhaps
it was the abortion.

227
00:19:54,494 --> 00:19:56,496
Somebody gave her morphine,

228
00:19:56,529 --> 00:20:01,334
and Brenda became London's
first and most notorious junkie.

229
00:20:04,871 --> 00:20:08,508
Scandal, drug busts, prison.

230
00:20:09,342 --> 00:20:11,978
Brenda became famous,

231
00:20:12,011 --> 00:20:14,514
but not in the way
she had wanted.

232
00:20:18,585 --> 00:20:22,589
Did she really think
she could stay young forever?

233
00:20:22,622 --> 00:20:25,492
Yes. Probably
in that moment we all did.

234
00:20:27,494 --> 00:20:30,530
We were just too tired
to break away.

235
00:20:31,498 --> 00:20:34,033
Eventually Brenda crashed,

236
00:20:34,066 --> 00:20:37,370
but by then nobody could
really remember or care.

237
00:20:37,904 --> 00:20:39,839
We were all crashing,

238
00:20:41,007 --> 00:20:43,710
and then
the whole world did too.

239
00:21:17,477 --> 00:21:19,646
[ American Girl ]
Adults were in a panic.

240
00:21:21,414 --> 00:21:25,385
But we were the ones
who would inherit this mess.

241
00:21:25,418 --> 00:21:28,755
[ Man Narrating On Recording ]
Today the largest single group
of the nation's unemployed...

242
00:21:28,788 --> 00:21:32,492
are young men and women
between the ages of 16 and 24.

243
00:21:32,525 --> 00:21:34,794
Boys like 18-year-old
Warren Harper,

244
00:21:34,827 --> 00:21:38,030
hardest hit of a generation
which has grown up
in depression.

245
00:21:38,064 --> 00:21:41,801
Warren himself never has had
a steady job in all his life,

246
00:21:41,834 --> 00:21:43,770
never has owned an overcoat.

247
00:21:43,803 --> 00:21:46,806
When he goes out
looking for work,
he wears borrowed clothing.

248
00:21:46,839 --> 00:21:48,908
He gets up late
and spends most of his time...

249
00:21:48,941 --> 00:21:51,811
hanging around
talking with other boys
who are out of work...

250
00:21:51,844 --> 00:21:55,748
and wondering
what's wrong when a fella
wants to work and can't.

251
00:22:03,490 --> 00:22:05,958
[ British Boy ]
You couldn't even work.

252
00:22:05,992 --> 00:22:08,961
I was fired at 16.

253
00:22:08,995 --> 00:22:13,366
The governor wanted
to take on an errand boy
who'd do my job cheaper.

254
00:22:15,535 --> 00:22:17,437
Nothing to do with my time.

255
00:22:17,470 --> 00:22:19,406
Nothing to spend.

256
00:22:20,473 --> 00:22:22,609
Nothing to do tomorrow,
nor the day after.

257
00:22:23,576 --> 00:22:26,379
I was a living corpse.

258
00:22:30,417 --> 00:22:32,819
[ German Girl ]
Not only old people had grief,

259
00:22:34,587 --> 00:22:36,623
but young ones too.

260
00:22:38,591 --> 00:22:41,628
Our future looked bleak.

261
00:22:46,733 --> 00:22:48,968
[ American Girl ]
Some parents
were suffering so bad...

262
00:22:49,001 --> 00:22:50,937
they couldn't look after
their children anymore.

263
00:22:54,641 --> 00:22:56,643
Those kids hit the road.

264
00:22:58,911 --> 00:23:01,714
They were the children's army.

265
00:23:01,748 --> 00:23:03,416
Hoboes,

266
00:23:03,450 --> 00:23:05,752
boxcar riders,

267
00:23:05,785 --> 00:23:07,620
young tramps.

268
00:23:11,157 --> 00:23:13,826
People thought
there was no hope for youth.

269
00:23:15,795 --> 00:23:18,798
But we were searching
for something to believe in.

270
00:23:19,766 --> 00:23:22,469
And we were willing
to fight for it.

271
00:23:22,502 --> 00:23:25,772
[ Shouting ]

272
00:23:25,805 --> 00:23:29,442
[ Man On Recording ]
As fast as one mob is broken up,
another gathers.

273
00:23:30,777 --> 00:23:33,179
[ American Girl ]
Politics was our problem too.

274
00:23:33,212 --> 00:23:36,048
We are not looking for charity.
We want an opportunity to work.

275
00:23:36,082 --> 00:23:38,551
[ Trolley Bell Dinging ]

276
00:23:40,820 --> 00:23:43,856
[ American Girl ]
There was talk of revolution.

277
00:23:43,890 --> 00:23:45,892
And they feared us.

278
00:23:49,829 --> 00:23:52,064
[ German Girl ]
There were the Communists...

279
00:23:52,098 --> 00:23:54,867
and the Nazis,

280
00:23:54,901 --> 00:23:56,936
and we took up sides.

281
00:23:59,906 --> 00:24:03,643
People would come up to you
in the street and ask,

282
00:24:03,676 --> 00:24:05,578
"Who are you with?"

283
00:24:06,546 --> 00:24:08,581
If you gave them
the wrong answer,

284
00:24:08,615 --> 00:24:10,182
they would attack.

285
00:24:10,216 --> 00:24:11,618
[ Shouting ]

286
00:24:11,651 --> 00:24:15,822
[ Man Speaking German ]

287
00:24:30,703 --> 00:24:33,072
[ British Boy ]
Radical change was in the air.

288
00:24:33,105 --> 00:24:35,875
[ Male Announcer On Recording ]
5,000 fascists rally
to their mobilization...

289
00:24:35,908 --> 00:24:37,944
for the much advertised march
through the East End.

290
00:24:37,977 --> 00:24:39,946
Communists jammed
the fascists' route,

291
00:24:39,979 --> 00:24:44,016
resisting the peaceful efforts
of the outnumbered police
to clear the way.

292
00:24:44,050 --> 00:24:47,887
[ British Boy ]
I was there when the fascists
started marching down my street.

293
00:24:49,288 --> 00:24:51,891
I wasn't gonna let
my country go that way.

294
00:24:54,627 --> 00:24:56,896
[ German Girl ]
We had to get involved.

295
00:24:57,964 --> 00:25:01,601
We weren't gonna be
another lost generation.

296
00:25:11,177 --> 00:25:15,915
[ President Franklin Roosevelt ]
Let us carry on the good
that the past has given us.

297
00:25:15,948 --> 00:25:19,719
The best of that good
is the spirit of America,

298
00:25:19,752 --> 00:25:23,623
and the spirit of America
is the spirit in which youth...

299
00:25:23,656 --> 00:25:28,127
can find the fulfillment
of its ideals.

300
00:25:28,160 --> 00:25:32,732
It is for the new generation
to participate
in the decision...

301
00:25:32,765 --> 00:25:35,334
and to give strength
and spirit...

302
00:25:35,367 --> 00:25:37,904
and continuity...

303
00:25:37,937 --> 00:25:42,875
to our government
and to our national life.

304
00:25:42,909 --> 00:25:44,811
[ Cheering ]

305
00:25:49,215 --> 00:25:53,019
[ Adolf Hitler Speaking German ]

306
00:26:15,975 --> 00:26:18,144
[ Cheering ]

307
00:26:51,277 --> 00:26:56,115
[ German Girl ]
Melita Maschmann was
a typical middle-class girl.

308
00:26:56,148 --> 00:27:00,753
Her parents complained about
the unemployment and poverty,

309
00:27:00,787 --> 00:27:02,889
but they didn't do a thing.

310
00:27:04,757 --> 00:27:06,893
Melita wanted action.

311
00:27:08,260 --> 00:27:10,663
So she joined the Hitler Youth.

312
00:27:14,233 --> 00:27:17,737
[ Melita ]
My mother expected me to be
unquestioning and obedient,

313
00:27:17,770 --> 00:27:19,739
like the maids.

314
00:27:20,439 --> 00:27:22,709
I rebelled.

315
00:27:22,742 --> 00:27:25,177
I wanted to be different--

316
00:27:26,713 --> 00:27:30,649
to escape from
my narrow childish life.

317
00:27:36,222 --> 00:27:39,091
I was a March Violet,

318
00:27:39,125 --> 00:27:43,229
one of the many youth who joined
after Hitler became chancellor.

319
00:27:54,073 --> 00:27:57,243
Every weekend we had tests
and competitions.

320
00:27:59,111 --> 00:28:03,415
Swimming, sports,
obstacle races.

321
00:28:03,449 --> 00:28:07,153
There were camping trips
and holidays too.

322
00:28:13,292 --> 00:28:16,262
I can only recall
this feeling of happiness--

323
00:28:18,865 --> 00:28:22,501
to be allowed
to belong to a community...

324
00:28:22,534 --> 00:28:26,038
which embraced
the whole youth of the nation.

325
00:28:39,251 --> 00:28:41,988
Millions of us joined
the Hitler Youth.

326
00:28:43,455 --> 00:28:45,958
It felt like the Wandervogel,

327
00:28:45,992 --> 00:28:50,229
only now we were part of
the national cause.

328
00:28:52,899 --> 00:28:55,134
Youth were leading youth.

329
00:28:59,371 --> 00:29:03,142
We were at the center
of the government's plan...

330
00:29:03,175 --> 00:29:06,078
because we would
shape the future.

331
00:29:13,419 --> 00:29:16,856
They wanted us to be strong.

332
00:29:16,889 --> 00:29:20,426
Hitler said his youth
should be tough as leather,

333
00:29:20,459 --> 00:29:22,962
swift as greyhounds...

334
00:29:22,995 --> 00:29:25,898
and hard as Krupp steel.

335
00:29:27,900 --> 00:29:30,269
A young German...

336
00:29:30,302 --> 00:29:33,772
was the most exciting thing
you could be.

337
00:29:45,017 --> 00:29:47,119
[ Man On Recording ]
Big-city backwoodsmen.

338
00:29:47,153 --> 00:29:48,988
New York boys
are getting back to nature...

339
00:29:49,021 --> 00:29:51,824
in the citizens conservation
camp at Yellowstone Park.

340
00:29:51,858 --> 00:29:53,559
That's pretty.

341
00:29:53,592 --> 00:29:57,163
An important part
of the national recovery program
are these camps,

342
00:29:57,196 --> 00:29:59,231
one of the president's
pet projects.

343
00:29:59,265 --> 00:30:02,168
They're a great thing
for city boys.

344
00:30:02,201 --> 00:30:06,072
[ American Girl ]
Roosevelt created the Civilian
Conservation Corps...

345
00:30:06,105 --> 00:30:09,208
and other programs
that put youth to work.

346
00:30:11,377 --> 00:30:14,981
It was job training,
but we were getting paid.

347
00:30:17,083 --> 00:30:19,952
Maybe our protests were heard.

348
00:30:28,360 --> 00:30:30,396
[ Man On Recording ]
On a bank of the Avon,

349
00:30:30,429 --> 00:30:33,265
you will find the men
of the first Grith Fyrd,

350
00:30:33,299 --> 00:30:35,101
or Peace Army camp,

351
00:30:35,134 --> 00:30:38,337
where young men
of all classes
can develop themselves...

352
00:30:38,370 --> 00:30:41,073
both physically and mentally.

353
00:30:41,107 --> 00:30:43,109
[ British Boy ]
We had labor camps.

354
00:30:44,376 --> 00:30:48,047
Instructional Centers
is what they were called.

355
00:30:48,080 --> 00:30:50,849
They gave us something
worthwhile to do.

356
00:30:59,291 --> 00:31:01,894
[ American Girl ]
The government
was taking us seriously.

357
00:31:02,995 --> 00:31:05,231
[ German Girl ]
It gave us a real boost.

358
00:31:06,665 --> 00:31:10,069
[ American Girl ]
Young people
were part of the solution.

359
00:31:10,102 --> 00:31:11,938
We were prospering.

360
00:31:14,040 --> 00:31:16,909
[ German Girl ]
And we were going to
change the world.

361
00:31:19,645 --> 00:31:22,982
* Happy days are here again

362
00:31:23,015 --> 00:31:26,652
* The skies above
are clear again *

363
00:31:26,685 --> 00:31:30,356
* Let us sing
a song of cheer again *

364
00:31:30,389 --> 00:31:34,393
* Happy days are here again *

365
00:31:34,426 --> 00:31:36,262
[ Cheering ]

366
00:31:36,295 --> 00:31:39,298
** [ Jazz ]

367
00:32:01,320 --> 00:32:05,291
[ American Boy ]
Let me tell you
in plain American English.

368
00:32:05,324 --> 00:32:07,059
I'm a jitterbug,

369
00:32:07,093 --> 00:32:09,495
and I'm crazy about swing.

370
00:32:12,064 --> 00:32:15,367
For years we oompahed
to sticky fox-trots.

371
00:32:15,401 --> 00:32:19,571
And then came swing
with its solid rhythm.

372
00:32:19,605 --> 00:32:21,740
** [ Continues ]

373
00:32:21,773 --> 00:32:25,111
Negro bands playing hot,

374
00:32:25,144 --> 00:32:27,213
but with the power
of a big orchestra.

375
00:32:28,747 --> 00:32:31,583
It was free, beautiful music,

376
00:32:31,617 --> 00:32:35,421
and it let us cut loose
and act like normal kids
for a change.

377
00:32:38,357 --> 00:32:42,561
[ Man Announcing ]
Every day into music shops
from coast to coast...

378
00:32:42,594 --> 00:32:44,596
go more and more customers,

379
00:32:44,630 --> 00:32:46,732
all for the same thing--

380
00:32:46,765 --> 00:32:48,767
the latest in swing music.

381
00:32:48,800 --> 00:32:51,337
[ Man #2 Announcing ]
Swing! Swing!

382
00:32:51,370 --> 00:32:54,473
It's the rhythm, rhythm, rhythm
that gets 'em.

383
00:32:54,506 --> 00:32:56,342
The hot-cha-cha,

384
00:32:56,375 --> 00:32:59,511
the boogie-woogie,
the vicey versa,
the nuts and bats.

385
00:32:59,545 --> 00:33:03,115
It's movement, movement,
rhythm, rhythm and all that.

386
00:33:08,720 --> 00:33:12,124
[ American Girl ]
Ever since the crash,
life's been so grim.

387
00:33:13,659 --> 00:33:16,995
Jitterbugs
were changing the mood.

388
00:33:19,198 --> 00:33:22,134
We were the new flaming youth.

389
00:33:26,672 --> 00:33:30,042
When Benny Goodman
played New York,
it was madness.

390
00:33:33,445 --> 00:33:36,448
There was a whole
youth craze catching on.

391
00:33:38,250 --> 00:33:40,386
[ American Boy ]
Adults weren't ready
to integrate,

392
00:33:41,487 --> 00:33:43,422
but jitterbugs were.

393
00:33:45,157 --> 00:33:48,026
White kids took their cues
from us Negroes.

394
00:33:49,095 --> 00:33:52,598
Where we couldn't go,
our songs would.

395
00:33:57,436 --> 00:34:01,607
Our music made the feet
of the world dance.

396
00:34:11,717 --> 00:34:15,454
[ American Girl ]
Swing broke out
to the mass audience.

397
00:34:17,356 --> 00:34:19,491
If you didn't
live in the city,

398
00:34:19,525 --> 00:34:21,427
then you could hear it
on the radio.

399
00:34:21,460 --> 00:34:23,362
[ Man ]
And so the Camel Caravan--

400
00:34:23,395 --> 00:34:26,632
[ American Girl ]
Shows like Camel Caravan
and Let's Dance.

401
00:34:26,665 --> 00:34:32,304
You could live the dream
without ever having
to leave your bedroom.

402
00:34:32,338 --> 00:34:35,807
[ President Franklin Roosevelt ]
I hereby dedicate...

403
00:34:35,841 --> 00:34:41,447
the World's Fair of 1939.

404
00:34:45,217 --> 00:34:47,619
[ American Girl ]
When they had the World's Fair,

405
00:34:47,653 --> 00:34:49,621
it was about the future,

406
00:34:49,655 --> 00:34:53,091
and jitterbugs
were at the center of it all.

407
00:34:54,626 --> 00:34:57,763
I heard them talking
about us on the radio.

408
00:34:57,796 --> 00:34:59,665
They said,

409
00:34:59,698 --> 00:35:02,768
"Once you've glimpsed
the world of tomorrow,

410
00:35:02,801 --> 00:35:05,171
you can never look back.

411
00:35:05,204 --> 00:35:07,873
You may enter it
a girl of today.

412
00:35:07,906 --> 00:35:10,909
You'll come out
a girl of tomorrow."

413
00:35:10,942 --> 00:35:13,612
[ Man On Recording ]
I want to tell you,
I have never seen...

414
00:35:13,645 --> 00:35:16,648
such a spectacle as this
in all my life.

415
00:35:16,682 --> 00:35:20,519
[ American Boy ]
Swing was the voice of youth,
the sound of freedom.

416
00:35:22,221 --> 00:35:23,889
It was real.

417
00:35:23,922 --> 00:35:25,591
It was alive.

418
00:35:25,624 --> 00:35:27,626
[ Man On Recording ]
Enthusiastic young jitterbugs--

419
00:35:27,659 --> 00:35:31,363
young Americans living
for the world of tomorrow.

420
00:36:13,339 --> 00:36:15,674
[ German Girl ]
When the Hitler Youth started,

421
00:36:15,707 --> 00:36:17,543
it was an inspiring cause.

422
00:36:20,512 --> 00:36:23,749
But now
it was the establishment.

423
00:36:25,517 --> 00:36:28,420
Membership
was compulsory.

424
00:36:29,321 --> 00:36:31,357
[ No Audible Dialogue ]

425
00:36:32,023 --> 00:36:35,761
Slowly, you lost yourself.

426
00:36:37,963 --> 00:36:42,701
It was the denial
and the degradation
of the individual...

427
00:36:42,734 --> 00:36:44,970
into the mass.

428
00:36:45,003 --> 00:36:47,273
[ Cheering ]

429
00:36:50,676 --> 00:36:52,578
[ No Audible Dialogue ]

430
00:37:01,687 --> 00:37:04,656
[ German Girl ]
If you didn't like it,

431
00:37:04,690 --> 00:37:06,792
there was no escape.

432
00:37:14,833 --> 00:37:16,668
At 16 and 17,

433
00:37:18,470 --> 00:37:21,307
you crawled inside yourself.

434
00:37:23,909 --> 00:37:25,611
Psychologically...

435
00:37:28,046 --> 00:37:30,382
you were armed.

436
00:37:38,490 --> 00:37:43,695
[ British Man On Recording ]
Germany has invaded Poland
and has bombed many towns.

437
00:37:43,729 --> 00:37:47,399
General mobilization
has been ordered
in Britain and France.

438
00:37:52,738 --> 00:37:56,575
[ German Girl ]
Melita had quickly climbed
the ranks of the Hitler Youth.

439
00:37:58,910 --> 00:38:04,583
Once the war started,
she left home to serve
as a youth press officer.

440
00:38:07,653 --> 00:38:10,088
Melita was
the ideal youth leader--

441
00:38:10,121 --> 00:38:13,725
rigorous, hardworking,

442
00:38:13,759 --> 00:38:16,762
and she believed in Germany's
superior moral position.

443
00:38:22,601 --> 00:38:25,404
She quickly lost
her Jewish friends,

444
00:38:25,437 --> 00:38:28,607
but sacrifices had to be made.

445
00:38:33,579 --> 00:38:36,748
[ Melita ]
You had only two choices--

446
00:38:36,782 --> 00:38:40,919
have Jewish friends
or be a National Socialist.

447
00:38:44,523 --> 00:38:48,059
When I had to pass
along the ghetto street,

448
00:38:48,093 --> 00:38:53,499
the wretchedness of the children
brought a lump into my throat.

449
00:38:56,702 --> 00:38:58,504
But gradually,

450
00:38:58,537 --> 00:39:02,340
I learned to switch off
my private feelings.

451
00:39:07,813 --> 00:39:11,617
Everything
that I was or had been...

452
00:39:11,650 --> 00:39:15,521
was now absorbed
into the whole.

453
00:39:32,037 --> 00:39:34,640
[ Laughter ]

454
00:39:42,648 --> 00:39:45,651
[ German Girl ]
Not everyone
was willing to comply.

455
00:39:48,654 --> 00:39:50,756
There were the Hamburg Swings.

456
00:39:52,090 --> 00:39:55,894
They were obsessed
with American music
and British fashion.

457
00:39:57,963 --> 00:40:00,832
It didn't matter
if it was against Nazi law.

458
00:40:04,503 --> 00:40:05,904
They had no manifesto.

459
00:40:07,906 --> 00:40:12,978
Still, their mere presence
was a threat to the regime.

460
00:40:21,820 --> 00:40:25,557
Tommie Scheel
fell in love with swing.

461
00:40:31,062 --> 00:40:35,000
It all started
when a friend of his
came back from New York...

462
00:40:35,033 --> 00:40:36,935
with all the latest records.

463
00:40:38,737 --> 00:40:41,940
Tommie heard something
in swing he liked.

464
00:40:43,008 --> 00:40:45,477
It was a new youth language,

465
00:40:45,511 --> 00:40:47,813
and Nazis weren't allowed.

466
00:40:50,682 --> 00:40:54,052
Once the war started,
if you weren't in uniform,

467
00:40:54,085 --> 00:40:57,823
everyone knew
what you believed in
or what you didn't.

468
00:41:00,058 --> 00:41:02,761
Tommie wore British suits.

469
00:41:02,794 --> 00:41:05,864
He wouldn't put on
the Hitler Youth uniform.

470
00:41:07,799 --> 00:41:11,970
It was important not to look
like faithful German younglings.

471
00:41:28,620 --> 00:41:30,956
The Nazis hated swing.

472
00:41:32,290 --> 00:41:35,627
They banned
all art and social dancing.

473
00:41:37,228 --> 00:41:40,098
Boys and girls
were forbidden to mix.

474
00:41:44,836 --> 00:41:47,773
Swing shows
were raided by police.

475
00:41:48,907 --> 00:41:51,910
When one Hamburg Swing
was arrested, they told him,

476
00:41:51,943 --> 00:41:55,647
"Anything that begins
with Duke Ellington...

477
00:41:55,681 --> 00:41:58,550
ends with an assassination
attempt on Hitler."

478
00:42:02,854 --> 00:42:06,692
So Tommie and his friends
met at his parents' house...

479
00:42:08,660 --> 00:42:10,929
where nobody
could see them dance.

480
00:42:35,954 --> 00:42:38,857
Once, for fun,

481
00:42:38,890 --> 00:42:41,760
they dressed up
like American gangsters...

482
00:42:41,793 --> 00:42:44,796
and pretended to rob
a friend's villa.

483
00:42:46,732 --> 00:42:48,834
Of course they took pictures.

484
00:42:50,101 --> 00:42:52,037
It was their art.

485
00:42:59,010 --> 00:43:01,713
Once the Gestapo
got ahold of the pictures,

486
00:43:03,715 --> 00:43:05,951
they wished
they'd never done it.

487
00:43:11,122 --> 00:43:14,860
Robbery charges
were brought against them.

488
00:43:16,261 --> 00:43:18,964
Police reports
called them criminals.

489
00:43:19,931 --> 00:43:22,400
It said
they were race defilers,

490
00:43:22,433 --> 00:43:24,069
they fornicated,

491
00:43:25,804 --> 00:43:28,173
they were homosexuals
and robbers.

492
00:43:30,742 --> 00:43:33,879
It wasn't just kids
having fun.

493
00:43:33,912 --> 00:43:36,848
They were a direct threat
to the nation.

494
00:43:47,859 --> 00:43:51,897
When they arrested Tommie,
they beat him.

495
00:43:53,431 --> 00:43:56,001
He was shipped
to a political prison,

496
00:43:56,034 --> 00:43:58,236
much like a concentration camp.

497
00:44:00,305 --> 00:44:02,841
He survived,

498
00:44:02,874 --> 00:44:06,778
eventually finding his way
to his beloved America.

499
00:44:10,315 --> 00:44:12,684
But most of his friends did not.

500
00:44:44,482 --> 00:44:49,120
[ President Franklin Roosevelt ]
A date which will live
in infamy.

501
00:44:49,154 --> 00:44:52,157
[ Man On Radio ]
Following yesterday's shattering
and unprovoked attacks,

502
00:44:52,190 --> 00:44:55,260
the United States
formally declared war
on the empire of Japan.

503
00:44:55,293 --> 00:44:57,462
[ Man #2 On Radio ]
Today the nation is stirring...

504
00:44:57,495 --> 00:44:59,931
as it slowly realizes
the immense extent...

505
00:44:59,965 --> 00:45:02,400
of the enterprise
on which it has embarked.

506
00:45:02,433 --> 00:45:04,836
More than 16 million
young Americans,

507
00:45:04,870 --> 00:45:08,139
in answer to the highest
obligation of their citizenship,

508
00:45:08,173 --> 00:45:11,743
place themselves at
the disposal of their country.

509
00:45:11,777 --> 00:45:14,780
I will obey the orders
of the president
of the United States...

510
00:45:14,813 --> 00:45:19,217
[ American Boy ]
The government was asking us
to defend freedom,

511
00:45:19,250 --> 00:45:21,319
and we answered the call.

512
00:45:24,255 --> 00:45:28,126
We thought democracy
was something worth
fighting for.

513
00:45:33,064 --> 00:45:35,366
[ British Boy ]
The Americans were coming.

514
00:45:35,400 --> 00:45:37,936
It was world war all over again.

515
00:45:37,969 --> 00:45:40,839
[ British Man On Recording ]
The youth of Britain certainly
means to play its part...

516
00:45:40,872 --> 00:45:42,273
in shaping the future.

517
00:45:42,307 --> 00:45:45,911
The authorities know how keen
all these boys of 17 are--

518
00:45:45,944 --> 00:45:48,113
a sign of the times.

519
00:45:50,281 --> 00:45:52,818
[ British Boy ]
We'd been at war
for two years now.

520
00:46:03,228 --> 00:46:05,230
I lived in London
during the Blitz.

521
00:46:07,899 --> 00:46:11,002
I slept in the Underground
while the bombs dropped,

522
00:46:15,173 --> 00:46:18,009
then came up to see
the buildings crumbling.

523
00:46:26,918 --> 00:46:29,787
I was excited when the G.I.s
arrived from America.

524
00:46:31,456 --> 00:46:35,293
They brought all the swing music
I'd been listening to
and made it live.

525
00:46:35,326 --> 00:46:38,129
Who wants to listen
to some sentimental ballad...

526
00:46:38,163 --> 00:46:40,832
when you're young
and you can dance
the "A" Train with the Yanks?

527
00:46:42,467 --> 00:46:45,303
The G.I.s looked so sharp,

528
00:46:45,336 --> 00:46:50,275
like we were in black and white
and here they came, in color.

529
00:46:52,577 --> 00:46:54,579
[ British Man On Recording ]
When you think of entertainment,

530
00:46:54,612 --> 00:46:58,083
you must somehow
think of Piccadilly,
the hub of entertainment.

531
00:46:58,116 --> 00:47:01,119
In Shaftesbury Avenue,
less than a hundred yards
from the circus,

532
00:47:01,152 --> 00:47:05,190
is Rainbow Corner,
famous American
entertainment headquarters.

533
00:47:05,223 --> 00:47:07,525
Ices and lasses,
and what more could you want?

534
00:47:07,558 --> 00:47:09,961
Unless it's
more lasses than ices.

535
00:47:12,130 --> 00:47:15,600
[ British Boy ]
Rainbow Corner
was open all day and all night.

536
00:47:15,633 --> 00:47:17,402
But sometimes
they had to close it...

537
00:47:17,435 --> 00:47:20,171
because there were so many of us
on the street outside.

538
00:47:23,108 --> 00:47:26,211
For a night,
I could forget about the war.

539
00:47:26,244 --> 00:47:28,246
[ British Man On Recording ]
And are they enjoying it.

540
00:47:28,279 --> 00:47:32,317
Such an occasion as this,
small though it may be
in itself,

541
00:47:32,350 --> 00:47:34,252
it's just another
happy indication...

542
00:47:34,285 --> 00:47:36,922
of the friendly relationship
and happy understanding...

543
00:47:36,955 --> 00:47:41,092
that exist between ourselves
and our cousins
across the Atlantic.

544
00:48:10,421 --> 00:48:13,391
[ American Boy ]
In Europe they were
treating us like equals.

545
00:48:16,127 --> 00:48:18,363
But back home
was a different story.

546
00:48:20,966 --> 00:48:23,168
We were the enemy.

547
00:48:28,706 --> 00:48:32,978
Warren Wall was 16
when the war started,

548
00:48:33,011 --> 00:48:35,380
the eldest
of seven brothers and sisters.

549
00:48:36,447 --> 00:48:39,384
He hoped to become
an electrical engineer.

550
00:48:46,757 --> 00:48:50,161
[ Warren ]
Sometimes I feel so alone.

551
00:48:54,299 --> 00:48:56,334
I don't wanna run
with the gangs.

552
00:48:59,337 --> 00:49:00,938
I wanna work...

553
00:49:02,040 --> 00:49:03,508
and gain respect.

554
00:49:05,176 --> 00:49:07,979
But most of my friends
don't see it that way.

555
00:49:09,180 --> 00:49:13,118
They tell me, why try to fit
into a white man's world?

556
00:49:17,488 --> 00:49:23,361
I don't believe I or any Negro
can help but feel inferior.

557
00:49:33,438 --> 00:49:37,108
Scouting's one program
where I'm nearly an equal.

558
00:49:38,643 --> 00:49:43,014
I can compete with white boys
and get the same recognition.

559
00:49:44,415 --> 00:49:48,119
I'd like to be
the first Negro Eagle Scout
in the city.

560
00:49:50,188 --> 00:49:52,523
But somehow I'm stuck.

561
00:49:54,225 --> 00:49:58,329
I don't know whether it's me
or the Scout leadership.

562
00:50:07,738 --> 00:50:10,575
I've always wanted
to be an athlete.

563
00:50:13,544 --> 00:50:16,414
And I know you can't give up
all your strength on girls...

564
00:50:16,447 --> 00:50:19,250
and expect to give your best
in athletic games.

565
00:50:21,619 --> 00:50:23,254
But when I was 14,

566
00:50:23,288 --> 00:50:26,591
I had sex for the first time
with a girl,

567
00:50:26,624 --> 00:50:29,160
and I thought I was hot stuff.

568
00:50:30,295 --> 00:50:33,064
I'll never forget
the experience...

569
00:50:34,265 --> 00:50:38,136
because for weeks
I was darn near eaten up.

570
00:50:38,169 --> 00:50:42,173
I had to go to my father,
and he just laughed.

571
00:51:13,871 --> 00:51:16,307
I've seen lots of people...

572
00:51:16,341 --> 00:51:19,510
whose actions
make me dislike them,

573
00:51:19,544 --> 00:51:21,512
even despise them.

574
00:51:24,749 --> 00:51:30,188
But my father says we should
be fighting for our rights,

575
00:51:30,221 --> 00:51:32,123
not picking fights.

576
00:51:38,529 --> 00:51:43,134
But at times,
I've just itched to take
a crack at a white guy...

577
00:51:43,168 --> 00:51:46,137
just to see if he can take it
like he can dish it.

578
00:51:48,239 --> 00:51:54,145
When I get disrespected,
I get so angry I could explode.

579
00:52:01,586 --> 00:52:05,456
[ Man On Radio ]
I want to appeal
to all the people of Harlem...

580
00:52:05,490 --> 00:52:08,526
for your complete cooperation...

581
00:52:08,559 --> 00:52:12,463
in order to bring
to a speedy end...

582
00:52:12,497 --> 00:52:16,301
this most
unfortunate condition...

583
00:52:16,334 --> 00:52:22,240
which was brought about
by a few rowdies and hoodlums.

584
00:52:22,273 --> 00:52:23,874
[ Man #2 On Radio ]
And during the past 10 days,

585
00:52:23,908 --> 00:52:25,776
the zoot-suit warfare
here in Los Angeles.

586
00:52:25,810 --> 00:52:30,515
Mobs attacked and roughed up
harmless citizens
of Mexican descent.

587
00:52:30,548 --> 00:52:34,285
Cars were stopped,
the occupants pulled out,
doors ripped from the cars.

588
00:52:34,319 --> 00:52:37,888
That's what happens when the mob
starts to take things
into its own hands.

589
00:52:37,922 --> 00:52:42,593
[ Sirens Blaring ]

590
00:52:42,627 --> 00:52:46,397
[ American Boy ]
Why would young people
fight for democracy...

591
00:52:46,431 --> 00:52:50,835
if we're just gonna be treated
like second-class citizens?

592
00:52:50,868 --> 00:52:53,571
[ Man ]
Aside from the physical
evidences of the war,

593
00:52:53,604 --> 00:52:57,975
the psychological
impact of the war
is of extreme importance...

594
00:52:58,008 --> 00:53:02,413
in consideration of the conduct
of the children at this time.

595
00:53:03,648 --> 00:53:05,850
[ American Boy ]
The lid had blown off,

596
00:53:05,883 --> 00:53:09,454
and all our anger poured out.

597
00:53:11,456 --> 00:53:14,892
And they searched
for a reason why.

598
00:53:14,925 --> 00:53:16,927
Have you ever had
any obsessions?

599
00:53:16,961 --> 00:53:19,964
Ideas that drive you
to do something?

600
00:53:19,997 --> 00:53:22,567
Well, yeah, I guess so.

601
00:53:22,600 --> 00:53:24,702
I remember when I was a kid
I used to have spells...

602
00:53:24,735 --> 00:53:28,539
where I was afraid
to touch a knife
for fear I'd cut my throat.

603
00:53:32,877 --> 00:53:35,246
[ Male Announcer On Recording ]
Upon America's youth,

604
00:53:35,280 --> 00:53:37,014
the excitement and
emotional tension of war...

605
00:53:37,047 --> 00:53:39,584
is today exerting
an influence...

606
00:53:39,617 --> 00:53:42,553
which psychiatrists fear
may be felt for years to come.

607
00:53:42,587 --> 00:53:48,359
And the conversion to all-out
war effort of American industry
and the American community...

608
00:53:48,393 --> 00:53:50,995
has confronted
many young people,
like their elders,

609
00:53:51,028 --> 00:53:54,665
with a profound
and unsettling change
in their manner of living.

610
00:53:58,669 --> 00:54:00,671
[ American Girl ]
The depression was long gone.

611
00:54:02,373 --> 00:54:04,809
Millions of people
were on the move,

612
00:54:04,842 --> 00:54:06,744
just going where the work was.

613
00:54:11,048 --> 00:54:13,751
Dad's working again all hours.

614
00:54:13,784 --> 00:54:15,820
Mom too.

615
00:54:15,853 --> 00:54:18,423
So I'm at home alone a lot.

616
00:54:19,724 --> 00:54:21,626
It gets a little lonely.

617
00:54:25,396 --> 00:54:27,965
[ Man On Recording ]
Freed from parental authority,

618
00:54:27,998 --> 00:54:31,736
youngsters are venturing
into new and unwholesome worlds.

619
00:54:31,769 --> 00:54:35,906
Experiments with new sensations,
such as the smoking
of marijuana,

620
00:54:35,940 --> 00:54:40,445
are tempting
more and more teenage youngsters
along dangerous paths.

621
00:54:43,080 --> 00:54:45,383
To many adolescent girls,

622
00:54:45,416 --> 00:54:47,552
even those
in their earliest teens,

623
00:54:47,585 --> 00:54:50,888
war is opening up avenues
of unaccustomed excitement.

624
00:54:52,423 --> 00:54:55,560
To them any man in uniform
seems a hero.

625
00:54:55,593 --> 00:54:58,796
And in towns crowded
with footloose soldiers
or sailors,

626
00:54:58,829 --> 00:55:03,401
it is easy for them
to get passing attention
they could not normally expect.

627
00:55:03,434 --> 00:55:06,070
Do you realize
what time it is?

628
00:55:06,103 --> 00:55:08,773
Oh, Mother, don't be such
an old fuddy-duddy.

629
00:55:12,009 --> 00:55:13,878
[ Glass Shatters ]

630
00:55:20,851 --> 00:55:22,487
No!

631
00:55:25,790 --> 00:55:30,695
Is it wise for a girl
of your age to go steady
with just one boy, June?

632
00:55:30,728 --> 00:55:35,433
Well, Miss Norton, I don't think
a girl should confine her
dating schedule to just one boy.

633
00:55:35,466 --> 00:55:38,436
She needs the companionship
of all of them.

634
00:55:38,469 --> 00:55:41,972
* There's a girl named Kate,
and she thinks
she's really great *

635
00:55:42,006 --> 00:55:43,741
* But she's not

636
00:55:46,577 --> 00:55:50,948
* All the boys stare
at the girl with blonde hair
It's not fair *

637
00:55:53,984 --> 00:55:56,587
[ American Girl ]
They called us Victory Girls.

638
00:55:56,621 --> 00:55:58,589
Khaki Whaki young women.

639
00:55:59,123 --> 00:56:00,791
Juvenile delinquents.

640
00:56:00,825 --> 00:56:02,627
Are you pregnant?

641
00:56:03,193 --> 00:56:05,596
Yes! Yes, I am!

642
00:56:06,163 --> 00:56:07,865
[ Tires Screeching ]

643
00:56:09,867 --> 00:56:11,469
[ Whistle Blows ]

644
00:56:11,502 --> 00:56:15,573
[ Male Announcer ] Johnny
and 200,000 other youngsters
who are arrested each year...

645
00:56:15,606 --> 00:56:18,409
are America's
number one crime problem.

646
00:56:19,510 --> 00:56:21,746
Now what will become
of this boy?

647
00:56:21,779 --> 00:56:25,149
Will he be
fingerprinted, photographed,

648
00:56:25,182 --> 00:56:29,554
given a permanent
criminal record at 15?

649
00:56:29,587 --> 00:56:32,089
Will he grow up
in reformatories and prisons...

650
00:56:32,122 --> 00:56:34,892
to become a bitter
and seasoned criminal?

651
00:56:36,160 --> 00:56:37,928
Can't something be done...

652
00:56:37,962 --> 00:56:42,099
to help
these twisted young lives
and set them straight?

653
00:56:42,132 --> 00:56:45,570
Golly, what do you suppose
is going to happen to us now?

654
00:56:54,111 --> 00:56:57,582
[ Male Announcer ]
To keep youngsters away
from dives and drinking places,

655
00:56:57,615 --> 00:56:59,750
there is the dry nightclub,

656
00:56:59,784 --> 00:57:03,688
organized and operated
by the local
young people themselves.

657
00:57:03,721 --> 00:57:06,491
Where they exist,
experience has shown...

658
00:57:06,524 --> 00:57:11,796
that most youngsters
prefer these clubs
to more dubious hangouts.

659
00:57:11,829 --> 00:57:15,065
[ American Boy ]
We had a right
to a place of our own.

660
00:57:15,099 --> 00:57:20,871
And adults started to realize
that maybe some freedom
might make us behave.

661
00:57:22,907 --> 00:57:25,843
So we started
our own social clubs.

662
00:57:27,111 --> 00:57:29,814
They were called teen canteens.

663
00:57:29,847 --> 00:57:32,082
[ Girl ]
This is fun, isn't it?
[ Boy ] Yeah!

664
00:57:32,116 --> 00:57:35,019
You're sure you like
to do things like this?
Sure.

665
00:57:35,052 --> 00:57:39,223
I thought all girls
wanted fellas to take them
to fancy places...

666
00:57:39,256 --> 00:57:42,727
and spend lots of money.
Not this girl.

667
00:57:42,760 --> 00:57:45,896
[ American Boy ]
We called the clubs
The Jive Hive,

668
00:57:45,930 --> 00:57:49,534
The Buzz Bucket,
The Swing Haven, Hepcat Hall,

669
00:57:49,567 --> 00:57:52,069
Rhythm Rocker,
Boogie and The Strut Hut.

670
00:57:52,102 --> 00:57:54,104
Hear the names?

671
00:57:54,138 --> 00:57:57,007
Proves that they're really ours.

672
00:57:57,041 --> 00:58:00,110
[ Announcer ]
The canteen has its own laws
about closing,

673
00:58:00,144 --> 00:58:02,112
and the members obey them.

674
00:58:02,146 --> 00:58:06,150
Some people may question
our behavior when we keep
the canteen open until 11:00.

675
00:58:06,183 --> 00:58:10,187
Nobody has to stay here
till 11:00 just because
the canteen is still open.

676
00:58:10,220 --> 00:58:13,658
There's no law that says you
have to stay or you have to go.

677
00:58:13,691 --> 00:58:17,595
I have heard people talking
about your late hours here.

678
00:58:17,628 --> 00:58:20,164
You'd better realize
that the town could pass a law.

679
00:58:20,197 --> 00:58:25,269
You see, whatever the community
decides is best for itself...

680
00:58:25,302 --> 00:58:27,071
usually becomes law.

681
00:58:27,104 --> 00:58:30,808
The community?
Well, aren't we part
of the community?

682
00:58:30,841 --> 00:58:32,643
Well, of course
you are, Jack.

683
00:58:32,677 --> 00:58:34,612
Don't you think
it would be better...

684
00:58:34,645 --> 00:58:38,849
if the canteen were
to pass its own law
to close weeknights at 10:30?

685
00:58:38,883 --> 00:58:43,187
[ Announcer ]
And so Jack is learning
about social controls.

686
00:58:43,220 --> 00:58:47,291
Social controls,
moral code and law...

687
00:58:47,324 --> 00:58:51,696
have always played a part
in the activities
of the teen canteen.

688
00:58:55,265 --> 00:58:56,934
These leaders--

689
00:58:56,967 --> 00:58:59,737
the Hitlers and the Goebbels
and the Görings...

690
00:58:59,770 --> 00:59:02,707
and, uh, so forth...

691
00:59:02,740 --> 00:59:06,611
have built up, uh--
I don't know--

692
00:59:06,644 --> 00:59:09,714
some sort
of a demi-godliness about them.

693
00:59:09,747 --> 00:59:13,718
The youth of Germany--
they have likes and dislikes,

694
00:59:13,751 --> 00:59:15,986
and they want freedom
just as much as other people do.

695
00:59:29,900 --> 00:59:31,702
[ German Girl ]
The tide turned...

696
00:59:33,337 --> 00:59:35,940
and bombs rained from the sky.

697
00:59:40,711 --> 00:59:43,347
There were sirens
every night...

698
00:59:43,380 --> 00:59:46,150
and several terrible attacks.

699
00:59:49,319 --> 00:59:52,056
We wanted to run away
from this misery.

700
00:59:54,424 --> 00:59:58,696
It didn't matter where to,
just away.

701
01:00:21,318 --> 01:00:23,120
Still,

702
01:00:23,153 --> 01:00:26,090
there were some
who resisted Hitler's will.

703
01:00:27,291 --> 01:00:28,592
For years,

704
01:00:28,625 --> 01:00:32,763
underground gangs
like the Edelweiss Pirates
escaped into nature--

705
01:00:34,398 --> 01:00:36,901
far away from the regime.

706
01:00:40,805 --> 01:00:44,241
They declared eternal war
on the Hitler Youth.

707
01:00:46,977 --> 01:00:48,245
In Cologne,

708
01:00:48,278 --> 01:00:51,816
they started a campaign
of anti-Hitler graffiti,

709
01:00:51,849 --> 01:00:54,885
vandalism and sabotage.

710
01:00:54,919 --> 01:00:59,123
In just one month
600 of them were arrested.

711
01:01:02,159 --> 01:01:05,863
The Gestapo made
an example of them.

712
01:01:12,202 --> 01:01:16,073
Kids of 13 or 14
were sent to the front.

713
01:01:20,310 --> 01:01:23,113
The old had sent us to die,

714
01:01:25,482 --> 01:01:27,952
and there was no turning back.

715
01:01:54,544 --> 01:01:58,715
[ Melita ]
My parents died in a night
bombing attack by the British.

716
01:02:00,851 --> 01:02:05,089
The sight of smoking ruins
became a daily occurrence.

717
01:02:12,396 --> 01:02:16,033
I believed that I would not
outlive the Third Reich.

718
01:02:18,568 --> 01:02:22,106
If it was condemned to go under,

719
01:02:22,139 --> 01:02:23,908
then so was I.

720
01:02:27,878 --> 01:02:31,882
I was no longer able
to suppress the realization...

721
01:02:33,550 --> 01:02:38,222
that all the sacrifices
had been in vain.

722
01:02:50,600 --> 01:02:55,405
** [ Piano: Soft ]

723
